{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionCompared with the widely used RGB frame cameras, which capture full-frame intensity data synchronously at fixed frame rates, Event cameras, also known as Dynamic Vision Sensors (DVS), have a significantly different biologically inspired imaging mechanism and perform better on lower energy consumption, higher dynamic range, and higher temporal resolution [23,24].",
    "As shown in Fig. 1, Event cameras capture the intensity changes in the scene, with each pixel asynchronously outputting binary information.",
    "Unlike conventional cameras, they do not produce video frames; instead, their output consists of event streams re-* Corresponding Author: Xiao Wang sembling point clouds.",
    "We usually adopt a quadruple (x, y, t, p) to denote an event point, where x and y are spatial coordinates, t is the timestamp, and p denotes polarity.",
    "Due to their asynchronous nature, this data is spatially sparse but temporally dense, and is free from issues such as motion blur."
  ]
}